<subSubSection pageId="25" pageNumber="26" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="25.[264,1323,937,1803]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">
<emphasis box="[264,383,937,962]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Diagnosis</emphasis>
: Body brown, tibiae largely yellow femora light brown; antennal segment III yellow; forewings brown with base paler. Antennae 7 (rarely 8)­segmented; ocellar setae III arise outside ocellar triangle; postocular seta II much smaller than I or III (
<figureCitation box="[1219,1308,1017,1043]" captionStart="FIGURES 26–37" captionStartId="24.[264,370,1786,1807]" captionTargetBox="[278,1308,291,1772]" captionTargetId="figure-63@24.[277,1311,286,1775]" captionTargetPageId="24" captionText="FIGURES 26–37. Thrips species. T. extensicornis 26–29: (26) Head &amp; pronotum; (27) Meso­metanota; (28) Tergites VI–VIII; (29) Sternites VI–VII. T. florum 30–32: (30) Meso­metanota; (31) Head; (32) Forewing clavus. T. hawaiiensis 33–35: (33) Meso­metanota; (34) Head; (35) Forewing clavus. T. hoddlei 36–37: (36) Head &amp; pronotum; (37) Meso­metanota." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5049486" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5049486/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Fig. 31</figureCitation>
). Pronotum with transverse markings, midlateral setae all equally weak, posterior sub­marginal apodeme weak. Mesonotum with no lines of sculpture close to anterior campaniform sensilla (
<figureCitation box="[371,462,1137,1163]" captionStart="FIGURES 26–37" captionStartId="24.[264,370,1786,1807]" captionTargetBox="[278,1308,291,1772]" captionTargetId="figure-63@24.[277,1311,286,1775]" captionTargetPageId="24" captionText="FIGURES 26–37. Thrips species. T. extensicornis 26–29: (26) Head &amp; pronotum; (27) Meso­metanota; (28) Tergites VI–VIII; (29) Sternites VI–VII. T. florum 30–32: (30) Meso­metanota; (31) Head; (32) Forewing clavus. T. hawaiiensis 33–35: (33) Meso­metanota; (34) Head; (35) Forewing clavus. T. hoddlei 36–37: (36) Head &amp; pronotum; (37) Meso­metanota." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5049486" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5049486/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Fig. 30</figureCitation>
). Metanotum transversely striate on anterior half, with longitudinal but more widely spaced striations on posterior half, median setae arise at anterior margin, campaniform sensilla present. Forewing first vein with 3 setae on distal half, clavus with subterminal seta longer than terminal seta (
<figureCitation box="[789,880,1257,1283]" captionStart="FIGURES 26–37" captionStartId="24.[264,370,1786,1807]" captionTargetBox="[278,1308,291,1772]" captionTargetId="figure-63@24.[277,1311,286,1775]" captionTargetPageId="24" captionText="FIGURES 26–37. Thrips species. T. extensicornis 26–29: (26) Head &amp; pronotum; (27) Meso­metanota; (28) Tergites VI–VIII; (29) Sternites VI–VII. T. florum 30–32: (30) Meso­metanota; (31) Head; (32) Forewing clavus. T. hawaiiensis 33–35: (33) Meso­metanota; (34) Head; (35) Forewing clavus. T. hoddlei 36–37: (36) Head &amp; pronotum; (37) Meso­metanota." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5049486" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5049486/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Fig. 32</figureCitation>
). Abdominal tergite II with 4 lateral setae; tergite VIII comb complete but short and irregular; sternites III–VII with 6–14 discal setae.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="25.[264,1323,937,1803]" box="[312,518,1377,1403]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Male pale brown.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="25.[264,1323,937,1803]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">
<emphasis box="[312,418,1417,1442]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Breeding</emphasis>
: This species has been recorded from the flowers of many plants, but although this suggest that it is highly polyphagous there appears to have been no attempt to recognise the range of larval hosts. Many records of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Schmutz, 1913:" authorityYear="1003" box="[886,993,1497,1522]" class="Insecta" family="Thripidae" genus="Thrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="florum">
<emphasis box="[886,993,1497,1522]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">T. florum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are likely to involve confusion with 
<taxonomicName box="[380,547,1537,1562]" class="Insecta" family="Thripidae" genus="Thrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hawaiiensis">
<emphasis box="[380,547,1537,1562]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">T. hawaiiensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="25.[264,1323,937,1803]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">
<emphasis box="[312,455,1577,1602]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Distribution</emphasis>
: This tropical species is widespread across Asia and the Pacific, and has also been recorded from Florida and the Caribbean (
<bibRefCitation author="Nakahara, S." box="[884,1076,1617,1643]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" pagination="1 - 183" refId="ref32180" refString="Nakahara, S. (1994) The genus Thrips Linnaeus (Thysanoptera: Thripidae) of the New World. United States Department of Agriculture. Technical Bulletin, 1822, 1 - 183." type="journal article" year="1994">Nakahara, 1994</bibRefCitation>
; Mound, &amp; Marullo, 1996). In 
<collectingCountry box="[379,489,1657,1683]" name="Australia" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Australia</collectingCountry>
, a few specimens have been taken in the coastal regions of 
<collectingRegion box="[1184,1322,1657,1683]" country="Australia" name="Queensland" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Queensland</collectingRegion>
north from Brisbane, and around Darwin in 
<collectingRegion box="[781,1000,1697,1723]" country="Australia" name="Northern Territory" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Northern Territory</collectingRegion>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="25.[264,1323,937,1803]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">
<emphasis box="[312,471,1737,1762]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Relationships</emphasis>
: This species is most closely related to 
<taxonomicName box="[933,1154,1737,1762]" class="Insecta" family="Thripidae" genus="Thrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hawaiiensis">
<emphasis box="[933,1154,1737,1762]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Thrips hawaiiensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, with which it has often been confused (
<bibRefCitation author="Bhatti, J. S." box="[562,726,1777,1803]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" pagination="31 - 53" refId="ref30079" refString="Bhatti, J. S. (1999 a) New characters for identification of the pest species Thrips hawaiiensis and florum (Terebrantia: Thripidae). Thrips, 1, 31 - 53." type="journal article" year="1999">Bhatti, 1999a</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
